# Which machine recorded embed-red-square-mean.csv, and which golden this
# describes. Read by helper-llm.R::golden_machine(); `key: value`, comments
# ignored. REGENERATE BOTH FILES TOGETHER -- the golden-update skill covers it.
#
# machine    = helper-llm.R::machine_fingerprint() on the recording machine. The
#              T2 pin is bit-exact only there; the test derives this string here
#              and skips elsewhere, rather than asking an operator to assert it
#              (hard rule 8d).
# golden-md5 = binds this sidecar to the golden's CONTENT (rule 8d again). If the
#              golden is re-recorded and this file is not, the mismatch is a LOUD
#              error on every platform -- not a pin that silently skips forever
#              because it is still gated on a machine that no longer exists.
#
# Why the CPU model is in the key and the arch is not enough: this pin measured
# max |d| = 6.05e-3 on a *non-M4 arm64* runner (same OS, same arch, same
# n_threads = 4). ggml keeps GGML_ACCELERATE on for the macOS CPU backend and
# dispatches on runtime CPU features; this machine reports FEAT_SME = 1 and
# FEAT_SME2 = 1, which earlier Apple Silicon does not have. Same architecture,
# different instructions, different floats -- by design, not by defect.
machine: Darwin | arm64 | Apple M4
golden-md5: b940fb2fe9961d35ecc48ecb238388b1
